{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4612bf77-f092-4a5d-8cc2-caf9580184d5","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2, which supports constructor injection for `TestContext`. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization, IAsyncCleanup\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // Constructor injection for TestContext (MSTest 3.3+)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous initialization here\n    }\n\n    // Async initialization (runs after constructor, before each test)\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // async setup work\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup (runs after each test)\n    public Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_testContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor injection** of `TestContext` replaces the old property-setter approach (available since MSTest 3.3).\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`** provides async per-test setup (replaces `[TestInitialize]` for async scenarios).\n- **`IAsyncCleanup`** provides async per-test teardown.\n- You can still use `[ClassInitialize]`/`[ClassCleanup]` for one-time static setup if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2033da3b-322f-4104-b856-3132de209273","outputTokens":356,"requestId":"E44E:3B8967:3D565B3:4387552:6A02FB75"},"id":"3f838260-f6aa-4f60-8ce5-e4ea135c48f5","timestamp":"2026-05-12T10:05:49.128Z","parentId":"4842e5f6-29ce-4dc7-a705-0da38ab36a54"}
